# /etc/sudoers.d/teslausb-cache-invalidate
#
# Allows the `teslausb` service user (which the web app and worker
# run as) to invoke `tesla_cache_invalidate.sh` with NO arguments,
# under root, without a password.
#
# Why NOPASSWD: the web request handler is non-interactive — there
# is no human at a TTY to type a password. The blast radius is
# intentionally limited (see below).
#
# Why "no-args only": the script's `--gadget`, `--function`, and
# `--lun` flags accept arbitrary strings. Even though the script
# validates them before constructing configfs paths, the principle
# of least authority says: the only call the service should ever
# need is the default (LUN 1 == media drive), so that is the only
# call sudoers allows. Diagnostics that want a non-default LUN must
# be invoked manually by an admin (separate `sudo` invocation,
# subject to the system sudoers policy, NOT this fragment).
#
# The trailing `""` after the command path is what restricts to
# zero arguments — without it, sudo's default is to allow ANY
# arguments. See sudoers(5) "Wildcards" / "Command arguments".
#
# Install:    /etc/sudoers.d/teslausb-cache-invalidate (root:root 0440)
# Owned by:   Phase 6 setup.sh (installs via `install -m 0440 -o root -g root`)
# Validates:  visudo -c -f /etc/sudoers.d/teslausb-cache-invalidate
#
# Defaults stanza scoped to this command only:
#   - env_reset (default; reaffirmed for clarity) wipes the caller's
#     env so the teslausb user CANNOT pass CONFIGFS_ROOT, GADGET,
#     FUNCTION, LUN, or EJECT_MS via env to redirect the script
#     elsewhere. The script falls back to its built-in defaults.
#   - !requiretty so the web request handler (no TTY) can invoke.
Defaults!/usr/local/bin/tesla_cache_invalidate.sh env_reset, !requiretty

teslausb ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/bin/tesla_cache_invalidate.sh ""
